# 🔐 CTF Write-up: Acropalypse KeePass Challenge

## 📌 Challenge Description

**Statement:**

An employee has lost his KeePass password. He couldn’t remember it and couldn’t find his password file. After hours of searching, it turns out that he had sent a screenshot of his passwords to one of his colleagues, but it’s still nowhere to be found.

He’s asking for your help to recover it.

**Given:**
- `chal42.zip`
- SHA256: `028c8561f087da873b08968d55141dcfc8f10a47e787f79c35b2da611a5e07ce`

---

## 📥 Initial Steps

First, I downloaded and extracted the provided zip file:

```bash
unzip chal42.zip
ls -l
This revealed two files:

Capture.png

Database.kdbx

🖼️ Image Analysis
I opened the image:

xdg-open Capture.png
The image appeared to be a screenshot of an Excel file containing several passwords. However, none of them seemed useful at first glance.

Upon closer inspection, I noticed a partial letter "K" on the middle-right side of the image. This seemed unusual and hinted that something might have been cropped out.

This led me to suspect that the image might be vulnerable to Acropalypse (a vulnerability where cropped images still contain recoverable data).

🛠️ Exploiting Acropalypse
To test this, I used the Acropalypse Multi-Tool GUI:

👉 https://github.com/frankthetank-music/Acropalypse-Multi-Tool

After loading Capture.png into the tool, I was able to recover additional hidden image data that had been cropped out.

🔍 Recovered Data
The recovered portion revealed a hidden password:

-=b9w9h^+j%\x-rMPUqv9Vv`@X%*=a
This confirmed that the image had indeed been improperly cropped and still contained sensitive information.

🔓 Accessing KeePass Database
Next, I used the recovered password to open the KeePass database:

File: Database.kdbx

Password: (recovered from image)

After successfully unlocking the database, I was able to retrieve the flag.

🏁 Flag

🧠 Key Takeaways
Cropping an image does not always remove the underlying data

The Acropalypse vulnerability can expose sensitive information from improperly edited images

Always properly sanitize or re-save images before sharing them

